muted.description: Used to create a low-contrast, subtle background that does not draw attention to itself. It's ideal for supporting content or areas that should remain in the background visually, allowing primary elements to stand out.

inset.description: Intended to give the impression of depth by making an area look "pushed in" or recessed. This can enhance the user experience by creating a sense of layers and separations between different UI components.

disabled.description: A disabled background color visually indicates that an element is non-interactive, differentiates it from active states, reduces distraction, and enhances accessibility by clearly signaling its inactive status.

emphasis.description: It's used to draw attention to specific elements or areas in a UI, such as alerts, highlights, or calls to action. It typically contrasts with the surrounding background to ensure visibility and emphasize importance or priority.

transparent.description: Commonly applied to Overlays and Modals: To maintain focus on specific elements while still revealing the context behind them.

inverse.description: An inverse background is used to provide contrast when elements are displayed on a background opposite to the standard color scheme, such as light text on a dark background or vice versa.
